---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import GlobeHero from '../components/GlobeHero.astro';
import DelayHeatmap from '../components/DelayHeatmap.astro';
import CrossfilterDash from '../components/CrossfilterDash.astro';
import FareComparison from '../components/FareComparison.astro';
import AnomalyList from '../components/AnomalyList.astro';
import ForecastChart from '../components/ForecastChart.astro';
import summary from '@data/airport_summary.json';

const airports = [
  { code: 'IAD', name: 'Dulles',  color: 'var(--iad)', ...summary.IAD },
  { code: 'DCA', name: 'Reagan',  color: 'var(--dca)', ...summary.DCA },
  { code: 'BWI', name: 'BWI',     color: 'var(--bwi)', ...summary.BWI },
] as const;

function pct(n: number) { return (n * 100).toFixed(1) + '%'; }
function fmt(n: number) { return n.toLocaleString(); }
function fmtk(n: number) { return n >= 1_000_000 ? (n / 1_000_000).toFixed(2) + 'M' : n >= 1_000 ? (n / 1_000).toFixed(0) + 'K' : String(n); }
---

<Layout>
  <GlobeHero />

  <!-- ── Section 1: Introduction ─────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>IAD, DCA, BWI — what ten years of data shows</h2>
      <p>
        Growing up in the DMV means you've always got three airports to pick from. IAD out
        in Chantilly, DCA right by the Potomac, BWI up in Baltimore.
      </p>
      <p>
        I live closest to IAD so it's usually my default. My flights to Taiwan go through
        there, though it still requires a layover so there's no real advantage over the other
        two. One summer I found Tokyo cheaper out of BWI than anything IAD was offering, which
        caught me off guard since I'd always assumed IAD had the best international fares. Most
        recently I flew out of IAD for Tampa for a cruise. Honestly, price is what drives my
        decision every time.
      </p>
      <p>
        Now I want to know whether IAD actually offers better fares, or whether the drive to DCA
        or BWI is worth it. So I pulled <strong>3.2 million flights</strong> from the Bureau of
        Transportation Statistics: 2,823,044 domestic and 335,719 international departures,
        along with T-100 capacity and DB1B fare surveys from the same source, joined with NOAA
        weather records.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Stat cards -->
    <div class="cards full-bleed">
      {airports.map(ap => (
        <div class="card">
          <div class="card-code" style={`color: ${ap.color}`}>{ap.code}</div>
          <div class="card-name">{ap.name}</div>
          <div class="card-stats">
            <div class="stat">
              <span class="stat-value">{fmt(ap.total_flights + (ap as any).intl_departures)}</span>
              <span class="stat-label">total flights</span>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <span class="stat-value">{pct(ap.late_rate)}</span>
              <span class="stat-label">arrived late†</span>
            </div>
            <div class="stat">
              <span class="stat-value">{pct(ap.cancel_rate)}</span>
              <span class="stat-label">cancelled†</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card-intl">+{fmtk((ap as any).intl_departures)} intl departures</div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
    <p class="cards-footnote full-bleed">† Domestic flights only — BTS on-time data covers domestic routes. "Arrived late" = 15+ min behind scheduled arrival.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 2: Crossfilter ───────────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Explore 2.7 million domestic flights</h2>
      <p>
        Filter by airport using the buttons above, then drag across any chart to select
        a range — date, hour of day, arrival delay, or flight distance. Every chart
        updates based on what you've selected in all the others, so dragging to morning
        flights in summer immediately shows how that changes the delay and distance
        distributions.
      </p>
      <p>
        The count starts at 2.7 million, not 3.2 million, for two reasons: 335,719
        international flights are excluded because BTS on-time data only covers domestic
        routes, and 75,040 cancelled flights are excluded because they have no arrival
        delay. That leaves 2,748,004 domestic flights that actually departed and landed.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-chart full-bleed">
      <CrossfilterDash />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 3: Fare comparison ──────────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Does it actually cost more to fly out of IAD?</h2>
      <p>
        52 destinations are served by all three airports with enough flights to compare
        directly. The trend line shows how average fares have moved since 2015. The dot
        plot puts IAD, DCA, and BWI side by side on each shared route — the further left
        the dot, the cheaper the airport for that city.
      </p>
      <p>
        BWI comes out cheapest on most routes. DCA is often the priciest. IAD sits in
        the middle — which means if you're driving past DCA to get to IAD, you're
        usually paying more for the privilege.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-chart full-bleed">
      <FareComparison />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 4: Delay heatmaps ──────────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>When delays happen</h2>
      <p>
        Morning flights are consistently the most reliable across all three airports.
        Summer (June–August) and winter (December–January) push late rates highest.
        Evening departures in July and August are the worst single combination —
        particularly at BWI, where the 6–9 pm window in summer tops 30%.
      </p>
      <p>
        Select an airport to explore its hour × month delay pattern. Each cell shows
        the fraction of flights that arrived more than 15 minutes late.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-chart prose">
      <DelayHeatmap />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 4: Anomalous routes ───────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Routes that keep misbehaving</h2>
      <p>
        Isolation Forest flagged 87 routes as persistently anomalous since 2022 —
        meaning their delay profile is a consistent outlier from the rest of the network,
        year after year. BWI dominates with 42 such routes, followed by DCA (30) and IAD (15).
        BWI→ATL has been flagged every year for five consecutive years.
      </p>
      <p>
        The bar shows how many of the post-2022 years each route was flagged.
        A route that scores 5/5 has been anomalous every year since 2022.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-chart prose">
      <AnomalyList />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 5: Forecasts ──────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>What the models say</h2>
      <p>
        Prophet models were fitted on monthly late rates from 2015–2021 and
        projected through 2026. The dashed line is the forecast; solid lines are actuals.
        The shaded band is the 95% confidence interval.
      </p>
      <p>
        IAD and DCA are tracking close to forecast. BWI is the outlier: it spiked
        well above its expected trend starting in 2022 and has only partially recovered —
        averaging +4 percentage points above forecast through 2024.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="section-chart prose">
      <ForecastChart />
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Section 6: Limitations ────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section>
    <div class="prose">
      <h2>Limitations</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>No international delay data — BTS on-time performance covers domestic flights only. International route arcs on the globe show passenger volume, not delays.</li>
        <li>No international fare data — DB1B is domestic only by design.</li>
        <li>NOAA weather coverage ends August 2025; 4.5% of rows have no weather features.</li>
        <li>DB1B is a 10% ticket sample — fare figures are estimates.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  /* Stat cards */
  .cards {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 1rem;
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    padding: 0 1.5rem;
  }
  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .cards {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      padding: 0 1.25rem;
      margin-top: 1.75rem;
    }
    .card { padding: 1.25rem; }
    .card-code { font-size: 1.5rem; }
  }
  .card {
    background: var(--surface);
    border-radius: 12px;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border: 1px solid #2a2d3a;
  }
  .card-code {
    font-size: 2rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    line-height: 1;
  }
  .card-name {
    color: var(--muted);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    margin: 0.25rem 0 1.25rem;
  }
  .card-stats {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.25rem;
  }
  .card-intl {
    margin-top: 0.65rem;
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    border-top: 1px solid #2a2d3a;
    padding-top: 0.5rem;
  }
  .stat {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.125rem;
  }
  .stat-value {
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #fff;
  }
  .stat-label {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  .section-chart {
    margin-top: 0;
  }
  .cards-footnote {
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin-top: 0.75rem;
    padding: 0 1.5rem;
  }

  ul {
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    color: var(--text);
  }
  ul li {
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem;
  }
</style>
